      <hedline>
        <hl1>Putting Teachers First</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Kenneth R Jolls on Aug 10 article on software intended to replace college classes</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>What's a body to think? While we hear from Dr. Roger C. Schank that ''software is going to replace classes as we know them,'' Clifford Stoll argued in an Op-Ed article in The New York Times in 1996 that ''kids are on-screen innocents who confuse form with content, sense with sensibility, ponderous words with weighty thoughts.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>What's a body to think? While we hear from Dr. Roger C. Schank that ''software is going to replace classes as we know them,'' Clifford Stoll argued in an Op-Ed article in The New York Times in 1996 that ''kids are on-screen innocents who confuse form with content, sense with sensibility, ponderous words with weighty thoughts.''</p>
        <p>Isn't the answer simply to find a balance? Let computers in education do what they do best: calculate, search, create spectacular graphics. Let people in education do what they do best: teach about values and other subjective matters that defy being quantified. Yes, a computer can be programmed to play the Eroica Symphony but not to shed a tear over the beauty of the music.</p>
        <p>KENNETH R. JOLLS  Ames, Iowa</p>
        <p>The writer is a chemical engineering professor at Iowa State University.</p>
      </block>
